<dl id="n51121a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n51" href="#n51121a">N51 (VI.B.44)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n51all.htm#n51121a"> 121(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the handwriting / on the face of / <font color="green">[him]</font> <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n51121a"><li>FW 135.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/lexfa.htm#n51121a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fa/l39fa.htm#n51121a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n51121a">MS BL 47476a-80</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:181 <a name="fad7" href="../../FF/fdra/fda.htm#fad7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fa/fad7.htm#n51121a">Draft: I.6&sect;1.7</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">In these <font color="green">[plays]</font> Mr. Irving secured his greatest triumphs. To the most eloquent expressions of face, to <mark>the handwriting, as it were, of the passions upon his features</mark>, he added a judgement of rare accuracy, the result obviously of close and earnest study and mature observation. In the &ldquo;Story of Waterloo&rdquo; he gave a most startling and vivid picture of senility, and once more proved himself possessed of wonderful adaptability. <small> Gaiety Theatre, Dublin. <a name="GTSV" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#GTSV"><cite title="source">Souvenir of the Twenty-fifth Anniversary of  the Opening of the Gaiety Theatre</cite></a> (1896) 32</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
